newsDetail.news19.description:
Dreams must come true — especially when they turn into clear plans that come to life, emphasized Hanna Tolstanova, Vice-Rector for Research at Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv, co-founder of the Professional Network of Research and Education Managers of Ukraine (PNRM Ukraine), and Board Member of the International Network of Research Management Societies (INORMS).

On 4–5 December 2025, the 3rd Annual Meeting of PNRM Ukraine members and partners took place at Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv, combined with the first All-Ukrainian training for science managers and administrators. The event gathered 85 science managers from 40 universities and research institutions across Ukraine.

The event became possible without grants or honoraria — thanks to the unity of people who share common values and strive to implement European practices.

Our main goal was to show that a science manager is not just technical support but a key person who helps the university grow and be successful. We wanted to give participants the opportunity to better understand their role and see how their work influences research quality and international cooperation.

The training also became a platform for sharing experience, discussing challenges, and finding new ideas for daily work.

The event took place in a very warm and friendly atmosphere, filled with openness, mutual support, and willingness to collaborate. Participants did not just listen to speakers — they actively engaged in discussions, asked questions, and shared their own stories.

We aimed for this training to be the first step in building a true professional community of science managers in Ukraine — people who are competitive, open to dialogue, and willing to learn and grow together.

PNRM expresses sincere gratitude to:
- Volodymyr Bugrov, Rector of Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv — for support and belief in the value of the initiative;
- Vice-Rectors for Research — for delegating staff of R&D Departments and participating in discussions;
- Olha Polotska, Executive Director of the National Research Foundation of Ukraine — for her welcome address and presentation of the Foundation’s opportunities;
- Ihor Taranov, Head of the Horizon Europe Office in Ukraine — for motivating work with Horizon Europe;
- Vladyslav Kondus, Head of the Research Department of Sumy State University — for openly sharing the secrets of effective management;
- Yana Sychikova, Vice-Rector for Research of Berdyansk State Pedagogical University — for practical tools on digitalization and AI use;
- Halyna Pravdzivia, Leading Economist of the Research Coordination Unit of Taras Shevchenko National University — for her practitioner’s insights;
- Vitalii Hryza, Senior Researcher at the Institute for Economics and Forecasting of the NAS of Ukraine — for explaining EU principles and experience;
- Anna Fomenko, Researcher and Lecturer at the International Management Program of the University of Applied Sciences in Wismar (Germany), PhD in Economics, Project Manager of EUComplianceM4UA — for the talk on compliance and scientific support;
- PNRM members Roman Nesterenko and Olena Pochaievets — for moderating the World Café and leading deep discussions;
- Oleksandr Kovalchuk, Vice-Rector for Research and Innovation of Kyiv National University of Construction and Architecture — for reviewing COST opportunities;
- PNRM members Oksana Shevchuk and Nataliia Butych — for sharing insights on international research management networks.

Special thanks to the organizations: Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv, the German-Ukrainian Academic Society, the National Research Foundation of Ukraine, Hochschule Wismar, and the EUComplianceM4UA project team — for their partnership and contribution to promoting compliance and European standards in research management.

To act based on real needs, the team began with a nationwide survey. The results revealed key challenges: the national grant system, budgeting, partner search, and professional self-realization of science managers, who often risk becoming merely a “service unit.”

Participants’ feedback confirmed that the training was important and timely. Therefore, work has already begun on the next step — the creation of the National Forum of Science Managers of Ukraine.

The Forum is planned in cooperation with key stakeholders: the National Research Foundation of Ukraine, the IP Office, the Horizon Europe Office, national COST coordinators, and the Rectors’ Union.

This is no longer a dream — it is a plan awaiting implementation.

Background: the idea to create a platform for professional development of Ukraine’s science managers emerged after participating in the INORMS Forum in May 2025. In September 2025, during a meeting of the Council of Vice-Rectors for Research in Odesa, plans to hold the first pilot training were approved.
